{{Politics of the European Union}}
An '''agency of the European Union''' is a decentralised body of the [[European Union]] (EU), which is distinct from the [[Institutions of the European Union|institutions]]. Agencies are established to accomplish specific tasks. Each agency has its own legal personality. Some answer the need to develop scientific or technical know-how in certain fields, others bring together different interest groups to facilitate dialogue at European and international level.

There are over 40 agencies, divided into 4 groups:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/about-eu/agencies/index_en.htm|title=Agencies and other EU bodies - European Union - European Commission|first=|last=Anonymous|date=5 July 2016|website=European Union}}</ref>

==Current agencies==
===Decentralised agencies===
Distinct from the EU institutions, the [https://europa.eu/european-union/about-eu/agencies/decentralised-agencies_en agencies] of the European Union are specialist bodies set up to advise the EU and Member States in areas that affect everyone living in the EU. They are located in countries across the EU, from Dublin to Helsinki, Tallinn to Lisbon providing services, information and know-how. The total budget of all the decentralised agencies is approximately 0.8% of the EU's annual [https://publications.europa.eu/en/publication-detail/-/publication/c7cd29b7-3712-11e7-a08e-01aa75ed71a1/language-en/format-PDF budget].

The [https://euagencies.eu/ EU Agencies Network] brings together more than 40 agencies to exchange information and good practices and increase the visibility of their work, helping to benefit institutions and citizens throughout the EU.

The [[European Space Agency]] has been proposed as a future agency of the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esa.int/esapub/br/br268/br268.pdf |title=ESA BR-268 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref>

