The '''Global Navigation Grid Code''' (GNGC) is a Chinese-developed point reference system designed for global [[navigation]]. It is similar in design to national grid reference systems used throughout the world. GNGC was based upon the work of the GeoSOT team, headquartered in the Institute of Remote Sensing and GIS, [[Peking University]]. The concept for this system was proposed in 2015 in Bin Li's dissertation: ''Navigation Computing Model of Global Navigation Grid Code''.<ref>Bin Li.Navigation Computing Model of Global Navigation Grid Code[D].Peking University，2015.</ref> GNGC allows easy calculation of space and spatial indexes and can be extended to the provide navigation mesh coding. Along with the [[Beidou navigation system]], GNGC provides independent intellectual property rights, globally applicable  standards and global navigation trellis code.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xyz3d.net/col.jsp?id=108|title=北京昊云科技有限公司|publisher=}}</ref>

==History==
From 2009-2013 a research team (the Institute of Remote Sensing and GIS School of Earth and Space Science located at Peking University), in conjunction with [[Wuhan University]], Information Engineering University, [[Chinese University of Science and Technology]], National University of Defense Technology, completed the National 973 Project: "Global Spatial Information Subdivision Theory and Application Method". As a result of this effort, the team proposed a global subdivision grid frame: Geographic Coordinate Subdivision Grid With One Dimension Integer Coding on 2<sup>n</sup> Tree (GeoSOT). This work solved the three scientific problems with regards to spatial data organization : basic frame, location code and presentation model.

This work resulted in 28 patent applications. The results of the project were published in a work entitled:  ''Introduction to Spatial Information Subdivision''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baike.baidu.com/view/8295845.htm|title=空间信息剖分组织导论|publisher=}}</ref>  

== Design ==
GeoSOT, is a grid system that originates from a center point on earth and climbs to another point at 50,000&nbsp;km altitude. It subdivides the earth according to 32 levels into millions of grids 1 cm<sup>2</sup> in size. The team proposed a complete area location coding system called "1+4 basic code, N serial extended codes".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coe.pku.edu.cn/research-news/3636|title=工学院程承旗实验室973计划项目“全球空天信息剖分组织机理及其应用方法研究”结题验收 - 科研新闻 - 北京大学工学院|publisher=}}</ref> Above these codes, the global subdivision grid code is a basic one and it has been completed.

GNGC is part of research on Global Sub-division Grid (GSG, or global discrete grid, geographic grid or spatial information grid). It subdivides the earth's surface into small cells. The research of GSG covers the methods of how to subdivide the earth into cells of equal size and shape at different levels. GSG improves the proficiency of the spatial information presentation and data organization. GSG is one of the key methods in geo-information science.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mt.sohu.com/20160420/n445218069.shtml|title=李博士谈网格之地理网格的概念|publisher=}}</ref>

== Applications ==
Main applications include geographic spatial data fusion, multi-source data fusion and geo-science comprehensive analysis.

It can mark location and position elements on a grid. The truing number coding design can simplify location area identification, expression and calculation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.point3d.net/nd.jsp?id=65&_np=4_11|title=中国推出面向全球导航应用的新网格编码GNGC|publisher=}}</ref>

