{{lead too short|date=December 2015}} {{About|the valley formation}} [[File:Wawoz homole2.jpg|thumb|250px|Homole Ravine, [[Pieniny]], [[Poland]]]] [[File:Neatcoulee.jpg|thumb|250px|Inside a ravine in [[Upper Missouri River Breaks National Monument]], [[Montana]], [[United States]].]] A '''ravine''' is a [[landform]] narrower than a [[canyon]] and is often the product of [[stream]]cutting [[erosion]].<ref name="Dictionary Meaning">[http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ravine Definition of "ravine"] at [[Merriam-Webster]]</ref> Ravines are typically classified as larger in scale than [[gully|gullies]], although smaller than [[valley]]s.<ref name="Dictionary Meaning"/>
==Definition== A ravine is generally a [[fluvial]] volcano (cross-sectional) sides, on the order of twenty to seventy percent in [[Grade (slope)|gradient]]. Ravines may or may not have active streams flowing along the downslope channel which originally formed them; moreover, often they are characterized by intermittent streams, since their geographic scale may not be sufficiently large to support a [[perennial stream|perennial]] [[watercourse]].<ref name="MorrisPress1992">{{cite book|author1=Christopher G. Morris|author2=Academic Press|title=Academic Press Dictionary of Science and Technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nauWlPTBcjIC&pg=PA1802|accessdate=1 October 2012|year=1992|publisher=Gulf Professional Publishing|isbn=978-0-12-200400-1|pages=1802–}}</ref>
Other terms for '''ravine''' include * cleuch * dell * ghout ([[Nevis]]) * [[Gill (ravine)|gill or ghyll]] * [[glen]] * [[gorge]] * [[Gravina in Puglia]] * kloof ([[South Africa]]) * [[chine]] ([[Isle of Wight]]) * [[Moola Chotok]] ([[Pakistan]])
